  "notes_for_integration": [
    "Node ids follow a `type:snake_case_name` convention to match darshana-graph / buddhist-philosophy-graph patterns; adjust prefixes if those graphs use a different convention.",
    "evidence_strength is mandatory on CORRELATES_WITH, MEDIATED_BY, EXPLAINED_BY edges so that thin-evidence claims (Seon hwadu, nembutsu, dhikr) are queryable and filterable separately from the well-evidenced core (Jhana, Vipassana, Dzogchen).",
    "ANALOGOUS_TO edges exist specifically to make explicit when a practice is being provisionally mapped onto a better-evidenced neighbor rather than having its own dedicated findings — this prevents silently smuggling in Vipassana's evidence as if it were hwadu's own.",
    "Citation nodes carry sample_size and study_design so queries can filter for e.g. 'exclude n=1 case studies' when assessing how much weight a claim should bear.",
    "CognitiveOperation nodes exist because Young et al. 2021 found no power-spectra differences between six traditions compared head-to-head — practices that look orthogonal phenomenologically can share low-level EEG signatures. The EMPLOYS edge lets the graph represent 'these two traditions differ doctrinally but share a cognitive operation' without that being read as a contradiction.",
    "Finding nodes + CAVEATED_BY edges exist so a null or complicating result can be attached directly to the claim it qualifies, rather than either (a) silently dropped, or (b) used to delete a real doctrinal/phenomenological distinction that the null result doesn't actually disprove — orthogonality here means phenomenologically/doctrinally distinct, not necessarily neurally separable at the power-spectrum level.",
    "Do not add specific novel Practice-to-NeuralSignature CORRELATES_WITH edges (e.g. 'hwadu -> high permutation entropy', 'nembutsu -> Sufi fanā' pathway') unless backed by an actual Citation node — several such mappings proposed in outside brainstorming documents were stated as settled fact without a supporting study, and should stay as ANALOGOUS_TO (confidence: low) or theoretical_only CORRELATES_WITH edges instead."
  ],
